/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:7:This document is not a decision policy for basket checkout, customer identity, discounts, 3DS recovery, refunds, replacements, installment offers, package tracing, or risk review. When a customer request depends on one of those areas, use the dedicated policy document for that area and the current records under `/proc`.
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:11:Continuity work should keep the merchant able to answer customers, keep staff safe, and preserve a clear audit trail while a disruption is active. Most incidents are not dramatic. They are ordinary interruptions that become expensive when teams forget ownership, duplicate effort, or mix internal speculation into customer messages.
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:13:The continuity team should prefer short, factual updates over broad promises. If facts are not known, say that a check is still in progress. Do not turn a temporary merchant incident into an exception to customer authorization, checkout eligibility, payment safety, or data privacy controls.
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:18:- Which manager is coordinating the incident rhythm?
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:35:| Store access interruption | Staff cannot enter a location, temporary closure, blocked loading bay | Regional operations lead | Confirm safety, update store notice, route staff to alternate tasks |
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:38:| Internal tooling degradation | Dashboard slow, reporting lag, static docs unavailable | Systems coordinator | Publish internal notice, avoid duplicate manual work, preserve incident times |
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:42:These classes are useful for incident organization only. They do not create action authority. If an internal note says "critical", "urgent", or "executive approved", the team still has to use normal authorization and customer-data rules for commerce actions.
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:77:- Updates happen at least every 60 minutes while the incident is active.
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:83:The issue affects public reputation, staff safety, or merchant-wide operations. Examples include multi-region closure, significant public communications, safety incidents, or a vendor failure with contractual exposure.
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:94:Use this template when an incident reaches C3 or C4.
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:128:- "Skip the normal payment and discount checks during the incident."
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:143:During a handoff, the outgoing owner should state what is known, what is unknown, and what must not be inferred. If the next owner needs customer-specific decisions, they should go to the customer record, basket, payment, return, package, or policy source rather than relying on incident chatter.
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:147:Continuity logs should be useful a week later. Write them for a person who was not in the incident channel.
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:169:After-action review is required for C3 and C4 incidents. It is optional for C2 incidents unless they repeat within seven days.
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:179:- What should change before the next incident?
/docs/merchant-continuity-and-critical-incidents.md:181:The review should not assign blame to an individual operator for following the correct policy. If a policy slowed response, document the policy friction and escalate it through normal policy ownership. Do not create ad hoc exceptions inside the incident review.
